            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What this birthday calculator shows</h2>
              <p>
                This birthday calculator goes far beyond a simple age counter.
                It uses your date of birth and an optional reference date to
                compute:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your exact age in years, months and days</li>
                <li>Your age in total days, hours and minutes</li>
                <li>The day of the week you were born</li>
                <li>The date and weekday of your next birthday</li>
                <li>How many days are left until your next birthday</li>
                <li>Your Western zodiac sign and Chinese zodiac animal</li>
                <li>How many birthdays you have already celebrated</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How age is calculated</h2>
              <p>
                Age is the difference between the reference date and your date
                of birth. The calculator uses calendar arithmetic, which is how
                age is normally counted in real life.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Age in years, months and days</h3>
              <p>To get the familiar <em>years–months–days</em> format, we:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Subtract the birth year from the reference year.</li>
                <li>Subtract the birth month from the reference month.</li>
                <li>Subtract the birth day from the reference day.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                If the day or month difference is negative, we “borrow” from the
                next higher unit:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If days &lt; 0, subtract 1 month and add the number of days in
                  the previous month.
                </li>
                <li>If months &lt; 0, subtract 1 year and add 12 months.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This method respects different month lengths (28–31 days) and
                leap years.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Age in days, hours and minutes</h3>
              <p>
                For total days, we take the difference in milliseconds between
                the two dates and divide:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  \(\text{days} = \left\lfloor \dfrac{\text{refDate} -
                  \text{birthDate}}{1000 \times 60 \times 60 \times 24}
                  \right\rfloor\)
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><code>hours = days × 24</code></li>
                <li><code>minutes = hours × 60</code></li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How the next birthday is found</h2>
              <p>
                The next birthday is the first occurrence of your birth month
                and day that is on or after the reference year.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Start with the reference year and your birth month/day.</li>
                <li>
                  If that date is earlier than the reference date, move to the
                  next year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The difference in days between the reference date and that
                  future date is “days until next birthday”.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                For people born on 29 February, the calculator treats 28
                February as the birthday in non‑leap years so that you still get
                a meaningful “next birthday” every year.
              </p>

              <h2>Western zodiac sign ranges</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator assigns your Western zodiac sign based on your
                birth month and day using the standard ranges:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Aries: March 21 – April 19</li>
                <li>Taurus: April 20 – May 20</li>
                <li>Gemini: May 21 – June 20</li>
                <li>Cancer: June 21 – July 22</li>
                <li>Leo: July 23 – August 22</li>
                <li>Virgo: August 23 – September 22</li>
                <li>Libra: September 23 – October 22</li>
                <li>Scorpio: October 23 – November 21</li>
                <li>Sagittarius: November 22 – December 21</li>
                <li>Capricorn: December 22 – January 19</li>
                <li>Aquarius: January 20 – February 18</li>
                <li>Pisces: February 19 – March 20</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Chinese zodiac cycle</h2>
              <p>
                The Chinese zodiac repeats every 12 years. This calculator uses
                your birth year to assign one of the following animals:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Rat, Ox, Tiger, Rabbit, Dragon, Snake, Horse, Goat, Monkey,
                  Rooster, Dog, Pig
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Internally, we map your birth year into this cycle using modular
                arithmetic:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \(\text{index} = (\text{year} - 1900) \bmod 12\)
              </div>

              <h2>Common questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I see my age on a specific date?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Set the reference date to any past or future date. The
                calculator will show how old you were or will be on that day,
                plus how many birthdays you had by then.
              </p>

              <h3>Does time of day matter?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool works with calendar dates only, not exact times. If
                you need sub‑day precision (to the hour or minute), you can
                approximate by assuming midnight on both dates.
              </p>

              <h3>Is my data stored?</h3>
              <p>
                No personal data is stored on the server. All calculations run
                in your browser, and you can clear everything with the Reset
                button.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2>Birthday calculator FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What does this birthday calculator do?</h3>
              <p>
                It instantly shows your age in multiple formats, your next
                birthday, the weekday you were born, your zodiac signs and
                several fun statistics like total days, hours and minutes lived.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use it for someone else’s birthday?</h3>
              <p>
                Absolutely. Enter any date of birth and, if needed, a custom
                reference date (for example, “How old will my child be on 1
                September 2030?”).
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why is my age in years slightly different from days ÷ 365?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Because calendar years are not all 365 days long. Leap years add
                an extra day, and months have different lengths. The calculator
                uses exact calendar math, not a simple 365‑day approximation.
              </p>

              <h3>How accurate are the zodiac signs?</h3>
              <p>
                The Western zodiac ranges are the standard ones used in most
                references. The Chinese zodiac is based on the Gregorian year
                only; if you were born near Chinese New Year and need the
                traditional lunar‑calendar assignment, consult a dedicated
                Chinese astrology resource.
              </p>

